{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.11,0.07,0.06,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2075"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"3527"},{"type":"tags","id":"3791"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6362"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman is referred to the Endocrine Clinic by her General Practitioner after she was found to have an elevated serum calcium level on routine blood tests following a recent episode of ureteric colic. She has been otherwise well. A subsequent blood test showed an elevated PTH (parathyroid hormone) level with normal renal function, and 24-hour urinary calcium is elevated. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and re-check calcium and PTH levels in six months","MRI of neck","Trial of oral bisphosphonates","4D CT scan of neck","Ultrasound of neck plus sestamibi scan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAs the main cause of primary hyperparathyroidism is a solitary parathyroid adenoma, the next step in management would be to image the neck in an attempt to localise the adenoma pre-operatively. If there were any concern for familial hypocalciuric hypercalcaemia, in which serum PTH is likewise elevated but 24-hour urinary calcium is low, surgical intervention is not warranted and patients are usually asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging the neck pre-operatively involves neck \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound and sestamibi scans\u003C/strong\u003E in the first instance. If these scans are concordant (i.e. both show a right superior adenoma, for example) then a focussed operation to identify and remove this parathyroid gland can be performed i.e. minimally invasive parathyroidectomy (MIP). If the imaging is negative or discordant, then a \u003Cstrong\u003E4D CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful, but patients will usually undergo a four gland neck exploration with removal of the largest abnormal looking parathyroid gland. There is no current role for\u003Cstrong\u003E MRI imaging\u003C/strong\u003E in the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical management with \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral bisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the priority: it is only indicated if there are concerns for osteoporosis, and would have no significant change on serum calcium or parathyroid hormone levels. Intravenous bisphosphonates may be used as a temporising measure prior to surgical intervention in severe, acute hypercalcaemia, but this is not the case in this otherwise well patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient would benefit from surgery based on her younger age, and critically, she is symptomatic from her hypercalcaemia (ureteric calculi), indicating she requires active intervention. Indications for conservative management, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ereview with repeat blood tests in six months,\u003C/strong\u003E include: asymptomatic; older than 50; serum calcium \u0026lt;3.0mmol/L; normal renal function; nil vertebral fracture or osteoporosis on bone mineral density scans; nil nephrolithiasis; and 24-hour urinary calcium excretion \u0026lt;400mg/day.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary hyperparathyroidism is most likely due to a parathyroid adenoma","Symptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism should be managed surgically","Imaging helps determine potential surgical approach"],"references":["Insogna KL, Primary Hyperparathyroidism. N Engl J Med 2018; 379:1050-9. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30207907/","Taniegra ED. Hyperparathyroidism. Am Fam Phys 2004; 69: 333-39. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14765772/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32190"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T21:32:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06